AWKA – Mr Olisa Igbonwa, who was rumoured to have been buried alive for taking a traditional title in one of the communities in Anambra State has visited the police to deny the story. The Anambra State Police Command in a statement signed by the public relations officer Ikenga Tochukwu, a Deputy Superintendent of Police (DSP) said the attention of the Command has also been drawn to the treading video clip. The police also released a photograph of Igbonwa when he visited the command. OAU Student: Retrial Of Adedoyin, 6 Others Begins In Osun Qatar Airways Debut In Kano The online video clip credited to one Ifeoma Okeke of Umunna TV  had shown some men closing a grave with mounds of sand as a narrator told viewers that one Chief Olisa Igbonwa was being buried alive in Alor, in Idemili South local council area by the Elders of Okebunoye village, Alor. The narrator claimed that the elders met and took a decision to bury and mourn Mr Igbonwa alive for taking ‘Ichie Ngene’ title by himself in the community contrary to custom and tradition. The Command said it received a formal complaint from Chief Olisa Igbonwa who said that he received a chieftaincy title from the traditional ruler of  Alor but was threatened by one Mr Uzoma Igbonwa and others to renounce the chieftaincy title within 30 days or he will face dare consequences. The statement said the Commissioner of Police Echeng Echeng has ordered for a discreet investigation into the matter to unravel the circumstances surrounding the incident in order to bring the perpetrators to book.